We can write the given system of linear equations as a matrix equation AX = B, where

A = \begin{bmatrix}
1 & -2 & 3 \\
2 & 1 & 5 \\
3 & 2 & 3
\end{bmatrix}

X = \begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y \\
z
\end{bmatrix}

B = \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
7 \\
4
\end{bmatrix}

To solve for X, we can find the inverse of matrix A and multiply it with matrix B:

X = A^{-1}B

First, let's find the inverse of matrix A. We will use the formula A^{-1} = (1/|A|)adj(A), where |A| is the determinant of A and adj(A) is the adjugate of A.

|A| = 1(1(3) - 5(2)) - (-2)(2(3) - 5(3)) + 3(2(2) - 1(3))
|A| = 1(-7) - (-2)(-3) + 3(1)
|A| = -7 + 6 + 3
|A| = 2

Now, let's find the adjugate of A:

adj(A) = \begin{bmatrix}
(1)(3) - (5)(2) & -(2)(3) - (5)(3) & (2)(2) - (1)(3) \\
-(2)(3) - (3)(2) & (1)(3) - (3)(3) & -(1)(2) - (3)(1) \\
(2)(1) - (1)(2) & -(1)(2) - (2)(1) & (1)(1) - (2)(-2)
\end{bmatrix}

adj(A) = \begin{bmatrix}
-7 & -15 & 1 \\
-12 & -6 & -5 \\
0 & -3 & 5
\end{bmatrix}

Now we can find A^{-1}:

A^{-1} = (1/2)adj(A) = \begin{bmatrix}
-7/2 & -15/2 & 1/2 \\
-6 & -3 & -5/2 \\
0 & -3/2 & 5/2
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we can find X by multiplying A^{-1} with B:

X = A^{-1}B = \begin{bmatrix}
-7/2 & -15/2 & 1/2 \\
-6 & -3 & -5/2 \\
0 & -3/2 & 5/2
\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
7 \\
4
\end{bmatrix}

X = \begin{bmatrix}
(-7/2)(1) + (-15/2)(7) + (1/2)(4) \\
(-6)(1) + (-3)(7) + (-5/2)(4) \\
(0)(1) + (-3/2)(7) + (5/2)(4)
\end{bmatrix}

X = \begin{bmatrix}
-7/2 - 105/2 + 2 \\
-6 - 21 - 10 \\
-21/2 + 10
\end{bmatrix}

X = \begin{bmatrix}
-110/2 + 2 \\
-37 \\
-1/2
\end{bmatrix}

X = \begin{bmatrix}
-54 \\
-37 \\
-1/2
\end{bmatrix}

So, the solution to the system of linear equations is x = -54, y = -37, and z = -1/2.
